<subSubSection pageNumber="720" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageNumber="720">
Hitchcock (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="720">Contr. U. S. Natl. Herb.</emphasis>
22: 140. 1920) reconsidered his earlier (1908) type choice, excluding the American plant in favour of a European concept for the species and Wiegand (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="720">Rhodora</emphasis>
23: 55. 1921) concurred with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hitchcock’s">Hitchcock's</normalizedToken>
reinterpretation. Baum (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="720">Canad. J. Bot.</emphasis>
45: 1846. 1967) also disagreed with the choice of a Kalm collection as type, though on the spurious grounds that 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kalm’s">Kalm's</normalizedToken>
name was not explicitly cited in the protologue. However, the Kalm collection is clearly original material for this name, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hitchcock’s">Hitchcock's</normalizedToken>
1908 type choice has priority.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
